5 Ive a born and raised las vegan. Ive never been to a chinese restaurant in vegas that has HAND PULLED NOODLES. this has to be the first one!  The owner/ chef comes out and prepares the hand pull noodles in the dining area.   You can tell by the quality and texture of hand pulled noodles!  Thanks Judd L for the recommendation!  The walnut shrimp were pretty big shrimps, tasty, and not tough!  Under the noodles with sauce, thats one of the selections where you can get hand pulled noodles. I got the chicken and mushroom sauce with hand pull noodles. it was delicious! it was flavorful and not salty! it's a good size bowl of noodles. You won't be disappointed with the size especially since its 6.95.   I also got the pork and chives pot stickers! they were turned updown which apparently is how its done in some places in china. it was crispy and delicious!  i will definitely be back because of their prices, quality, flavor, and cleanliness.   If know Mandarin, most of the employees speak that dialect.
5 tried more today - the wontons in chili oil - shaped like tiny goldfish - are insanely delicious.   They're perfect for chopstix competitions and for looking like a total dork - trust me, if you're uncoordinated, use your fork - or you'll have a Pretty Woman moment and watch helplessly as one goes flying through the air onto the floor or into your dining companion's lap.  vegetable pancake - delicious.  the crust is hand twisted and is art.  They make a dumpling with the same filling.    spicy noodles in the appetizer section is a refreshing noodle salad - a hidden gem.   tried the beef and onion dumplings today - finally got my lacey top hat - and they were worth waiting for.  Be sure and ask for the special homemade spicy sauce...   We learned a secret today - you can substitute any of their noodles in any of their dishes,even at lunch - so today we had spicy Szechuan chicken with beveled noodles.  I had to reacquaint myself with my tide to go because I made an epic mess of my shirt...but it was worth it.   These are noodles unlike anything you've had before, unless you grew up on them...   Toya, the lead in the front of house, visited with me today.  She explained that her husband, who was the noodle chef brought over to be the demo noodle chef at B#9 at Caesars, still works there -- and runs this restaurant with her.  He has two students who work with him - and they alternate between the two restaurants.  (Actually I think this is brilliant - Lord knows we need to train more folks to be good noodle pullers and to love Vegas...)  and how awesome is it that we don't have to go to the strip (or to Chinatown) to have cuisine this authentic, this handmade, this delicious.    They do deliver - but only within a 2 mile radius.  Fortunately they're on my way home from work...but at night, they actually have noodle pulling demos - as you can see from the pics below.  And nothing tastes the same after a long car ride home in syrofoam... but this is the kind of Chinese food that makes you wonder why you ever suffer the injustices done by bad neighborhood delivery joints.  The rubbery dumplings (if you can insult dumplings by calling them that)...the msg laden glop, the revolting fried whatever that all tastes the same.  Oh this is such a thing of beauty, this restaurant.    I just can't get enough of the appetizers...but do be kind...if they're busy at lunch, don't order them - because I learned today it takes 8 minutes to do one order of the lacey dumplings alone...  and because all their food is from scratch - she hates disappointing folks - and backing up the kitchen.  I can understand that - and respect her - and I want their business to be booming - just not when I'm there so I can drown myself in their dumpling deliciousness.  I'd die happy.  go, eat.
