4 It felt strange heading east and not west to Spring Mountain Chinatown for Asian food. No crazy drivers to avoid and no fighting for a parking space. Beijing Noodle is East of the strip on Flamingo & Sandhill and parking is a breeze. The restaurant is small with only about ten tables but clean.   The service was a little spotty - it took a while to get my order placed and the woman kept asking me from across the room if I had ordered with the waiter which I told her no several times. She finally came over and took my order.   My order the pork and chive pan fried dumplings with dipping sauce and I followed with the beef nugget soup with the flat pulled noodles. The dumplings were decent but I noticed only one side of the dumplings was pan fried and some of the inside was only lukewarm! The Beef nugget soup was flavorful and contained black fungus mushroom which was a first I've seen in Beef noodle soup. The hand made noodles were definitely the spotlight of the soup. Beijing Noodle Cafe claims they use no MSG which is a plus too.   I would probably return here again to try some of their other entrees which seemed unique compared to other Chinese restaurants.
