1 Having taken a great meal on Monday night at Caesar's, I had the urge to visit a great noodle house.on Tuesday.  Located in a strip mall, there was plenty of parking at 7PM, and I entered a somewhat humble establishment, complete with low-volume Chinese background music.  Being the only person in there, apparently the food server/cashier decided to put something more appropriate to my ethnicity, so a loud 80's something that may pass for music in some circles was placed on the sound system.  When he came to take my order, I asked him to either turn it down, or off.  "Which one" he asked.  "Pick the one you put on just before I complained," I said.  Quickly, the melodic sounds of Chinese background music could be heard, and my calm quickly returned.  I ordered a noodle bowl with chicken and vegetables - spicy - and waited a short time, enjoying my beverage.  Soon I was greeted to a normal sized portion of noodles, with the thin pieced of chicken breast on top.  I suppose there were vegetables, but they were scarce if any.  The noodles were a decent, rather thick consistency, probably of the size of linguine if it were round. Before the food server left, I asked for chop sticks and chili paste.  chop sticks were provided (plastic ones) but Chili Paste they do not have; hot chili oil is on the table.  Literally, the chicken had no taste - but an unusual smell that I could not determine was a spice I am not familiar with, or the smell of chicken not-quite right.  Dumping what remained of the Chili Oil did nothing to conceal the faint odor, so the chicken was pushed aside and the noodles eaten.  Somewhat rubbery and chewy, served without broth, they serve as a testimonial that Chinese food, like life, is a journey.  Shortly after my meal, I informed the food server of my questionable take on the chicken, paid and left.   It was a rather rushed trip; no more than 15 minutes later, the questionable meal was once more in a bowl, however this time one that flushed.  No further ill effects, and I visited Terrible Herbt's Casino for their $7.77 Filet and Lobster  (which is $9.77 if you are not a Club Card holder.)
